Boil a #kettle{} full. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into small 2cm chunks 
(peel first if you prefer).

Pour the boiled water into a #saucepan{} with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

Add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a knife 
through, ~{15-18%minutes}.

While the potatoes cook, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @pork mince{240%g} and onion and fry until browned, 
~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it cooks, then drain 
and discard any excess fat.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. 
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. 
> It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the mince is browned, add the garlic and @Central American style spice mix{1%tsp} (add less if you'd prefer things milder). Stir-fry for ~{30%secs}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1%400g can}, @chicken stock paste{10%g}, 
@sugar{1%tsp} and @water{75%ml}.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, 
until thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Meanwhile, grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60%g} with a #grater{}.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan, 
off the heat.

Add the @butter{20%g} and a splash of @?milk{} and mash until smooth with a 
#potato masher{}.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

Once the tomato sauce has thickened, stir through the @peas{120%g}.

Cook until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed, then remove from the heat.

When everything's ready, serve the spiced pork ragu alongside the buttery mash.

Finish by scattering the cheese all over. Enjoy!